# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: succinct-index-structure
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] A **bit array** (also known as **bit map**, **bit set**, **bit string**, or **bit vector**) is an array data structure that compactly stores bits.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] It can be used to implement a simple set data structure.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] A bit array is effective at exploiting bit-level parallelism in hardware to perform operations quickly.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] A typical bit array stores *kw* bits, where *w* is the number of bits in the unit of storage, such as a byte or word, and *k* is some positive integer.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] If *w* does not divide the number of bits to be stored, some space is wasted due to internal fragmentation.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] A bit array is a mapping from some domain (almost always a range of integers) to values in the set $\{{\texttt {0}},{\texttt {1}}\}$ .
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] The values can be interpreted as dark/light, absent/present, locked/unlocked, valid/invalid, et cetera.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] The point is that there are only two possible values, so they can be stored in one bit.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] As with other arrays, the access to a single bit can be managed by applying an index to the array.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Assuming its size (or length) to be *n* bits, the array can be used to specify a subset of the domain (e.g. $\{0,1,2,...,n-1\}$ ), where a 1-bit indicates the presence and a 0-bit the absence of a number in the set.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] This set data structure uses about *n*/*w* words of space, where *w* is the number of bits in each machine word.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Whether the least significant bit (of the word) or the most significant bit indicates the smallest-index number is largely irrelevant, but the former tends to be preferred (on little-endian machines).
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] A finite binary relation may be represented by a bit array called a logical matrix.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] In the calculus of relations, these arrays are composed with matrix multiplication where the arithmetic is Boolean, and such a composition represents composition of relations.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Although most machines are not able to address individual bits in memory, nor have instructions to manipulate single bits, each bit in a word can be singled out and manipulated using bitwise operations.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] To obtain the bit mask needed for these operations, we can use a bit shift operator to shift the number 1 to the left by the appropriate number of places, as well as bitwise negation if necessary.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] If we wish to iterate through the bits of a bit array, we can do this efficiently using a doubly nested loop that loops through each word, one at a time.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Both of these code samples exhibit ideal locality of reference, which will subsequently receive large performance boost from a data cache.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] If a cache line is *k* words, only about *n*/*wk* cache misses will occur.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] As with character strings it is straightforward to define *length*, *substring*, lexicographical *compare*, *concatenation*, *reverse* operations.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] The implementation of some of these operations is sensitive to endianness.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] If we wish to find the number of 1 bits in a bit array, sometimes called the population count or Hamming weight, there are efficient branch-free algorithms that can compute the number of bits in a word using a series of simple bit operations.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] We simply run such an algorithm on each word and keep a running total.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] See the Hamming weight article for examples of an efficient implementation.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Vertical flipping of a one-bit-per-pixel image, or some FFT algorithms, requires flipping the bits of individual words (so `b31 b30 ... b0` becomes `b0 ... b30 b31`).
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] The find first set or *find first one* operation identifies the index or position of the 1-bit with the smallest index in an array, and has widespread hardware support (for arrays not larger than a word) and efficient algorithms for its computation.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] When a priority queue is stored in a bit array, find first one can be used to identify the highest priority element in the queue.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] To expand a word-size *find first one* to longer arrays, one can find the first nonzero word and then run *find first one* on that word.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] The related operations *find first zero*, *count leading zeros*, *count leading ones*, *count trailing zeros*, *count trailing ones*, and *log base 2* (see find first set) can also be extended to a bit array in a straightforward manner.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] A bit array is the most dense storage for "random" bits, that is, where each bit is equally likely to be 0 or 1, and each one is independent.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] But most data are not random, so it may be possible to store it more compactly.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] For example, the data of a typical fax image is not random and can be compressed.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Run-length encoding is commonly used to compress these long streams.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] However, most compressed data formats are not so easy to access randomly; also by compressing bit arrays too aggressively we run the risk of losing the benefits due to bit-level parallelism (vectorization).
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Thus, instead of compressing bit arrays as streams of bits, we might compress them as streams of bytes or words (see Bitmap index (compression)).
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] However, bit arrays are not the solution to everything.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Because of their compactness, bit arrays have a number of applications in areas where space or efficiency is at a premium.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Most commonly, they are used to represent a simple group of Boolean flags or an ordered sequence of Boolean values.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Bit arrays are used for priority queues, where the bit at index *k* is set if and only if *k* is in the queue; this data structure is used, for example, by the Linux kernel, and benefits strongly from a find-first-zero operation in hardware.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Bit arrays can be used for the allocation of memory pages, inodes, disk sectors, etc.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] In such cases, the term *bitmap* may be used.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] However, this term is frequently used to refer to raster images, which may use multiple bits per pixel.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Another application of bit arrays is the Bloom filter, a probabilistic set data structure that can store large sets in a small space in exchange for a small probability of error.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] It is also possible to build probabilistic hash tables based on bit arrays that accept either false positives or false negatives.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Bit arrays and the operations on them are also important for constructing succinct data structures, which use close to the minimum possible space.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] In this context, operations like finding the *n*th 1 bit or counting the number of 1 bits up to a certain position become important.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Bit arrays are also a useful abstraction for examining streams of compressed data, which often contain elements that occupy portions of bytes or are not byte-aligned.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] For example, the compressed Huffman coding representation of a single 8-bit character can be anywhere from 1 to 255 bits long.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] In information retrieval, bit arrays are a good representation for the posting lists of very frequent terms.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] If we compute the gaps between adjacent values in a list of strictly increasing integers and encode them using unary coding, the result is a bit array with a 1 bit in the *n*th position if and only if *n* is in the list.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] The implied probability of a gap of *n* is 1/2*n*.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] This is also the special case of Golomb coding where the parameter M is 1; this parameter is only normally selected when −log(2 − *p*) / log(1 − *p*) ≤ 1, or roughly the term occurs in at least 38% of documents.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Given a big file of IPv4 addresses (more than 100 GB) — we need to count unique addresses.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Bit arrays are widely supported in programming languages, either through dedicated interfaces or more general bit manipulation capabilities.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] The APL programming language fully supports bit arrays of arbitrary shape and size as a Boolean datatype distinct from integers.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] All major implementations (Dyalog APL, APL2, APL Next, NARS2000, Gnu APL, etc.) pack the bits densely into whatever size the machine word is.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Bits may be accessed individually via the usual indexing notation (for example, `A[3]`) as well as through all of the usual primitive functions and operators where they are often operated on using a special case algorithm such as summing the bits via a table lookup of bytes.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] The C programming language's *bit fields*, pseudo-objects found in structs with size equal to some number of bits, are in fact small bit arrays; they are limited in that they cannot span words.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Although they give a convenient syntax, the bits are still accessed using bytewise operators on most machines, and they can only be defined statically (like C's static arrays, their sizes are fixed at compile-time).
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] It is also a common idiom for C programmers to use words as small bit arrays and access bits of them using bit operators.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] A widely available header file included in the X11 system, `<xtrapbits.h>`, is “a portable way for systems to define bit field manipulation of arrays of bits.” A more explanatory description of aforementioned approach can be found in the comp.lang.c faq.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] In C++, although individual `bool`s typically occupy the same space as a byte or an integer, the STL type `std::vector<bool>` is a partial template specialization in which bits are packed as a space efficiency optimization.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Since bytes (and not bits) are the smallest addressable unit in C++, the `[]` operator does *not* return a reference to an element, but instead returns a proxy reference.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] This might seem a minor point, but it means that `vector<bool>` is *not* a standard STL container, which is why the use of `vector<bool>` is generally discouraged.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Another unique STL class, `std::bitset`, creates a vector of bits fixed at a particular size at compile-time, and in its interface and syntax more resembles the idiomatic use of words as bit sets by C programmers.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] It also has some additional power, such as the ability to efficiently count the number of bits that are set.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Like array, the size of `bitset` must be specified at compile time, and cannot be inferred by the compiler.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] The Boost C++ Libraries provides a `boost::dynamic_bitset` class whose size is specified at run-time.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] The D programming language provides bit arrays in its standard library, Phobos, in `std.bitmanip`.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] As in C++, the [] operator does not return a reference, since individual bits are not directly addressable on most hardware, but instead returns a `bool`.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] In Java, the class `BitSet` (`java.util.BitSet`) creates a bit array that is then manipulated with functions named after bitwise operators familiar to C programmers.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Unlike the `bitset` in C++, the Java `BitSet` does not have a "size" state (it has an effectively infinite size, initialized with 0 bits); a bit can be set or tested at any index.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] In addition, there is a class `EnumSet` (`java.util.EnumSet`), which represents a Set of values of an enumerated type internally as a bit vector, as a safer alternative to bit fields.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] The .NET Framework supplies a `Systems.Collections.BitArray` collection class.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] It stores bits using an array of type `int` (each element in the array usually represents 32 bits).
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] The class supports random access and bitwise operators, can be iterated over, and its `Length` property can be changed to grow or truncate it.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Although Standard ML has no support for bit arrays, Standard ML of New Jersey has an extension, the `BitArray` structure, in its SML/NJ Library.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] It is not fixed in size and supports set operations and bit operations, including, unusually, shift operations.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] In Perl, strings can be used as expandable bit arrays.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] They can be manipulated using the usual bitwise operators (`~ | & ^`), and individual bits can be tested and set using the *vec* function.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] In Ruby, one can access (but not set) a bit of an integer (`Fixnum` or `Bignum`) using the bracket operator (`[]`), as if it were an array of bits.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Rust supports using native numeric types as fixed-width bit arrays using bitwise operations.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Third party libraries like `bitvec` provide dedicated interfaces.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Apple's Core Foundation library contains CFBitVector and CFMutableBitVector structures.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] PL/I supports arrays of *bit strings* of arbitrary length, which may be either fixed-length or varying.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] The array elements may be *aligned*— each element begins on a byte or word boundary— or *unaligned*— elements immediately follow each other with no padding.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] PL/pgSQL and PostgreSQL's SQL support *bit strings* as native type.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] There are two SQL bit types: bit(*`n`*) and bit varying(*`n`*), where *`n`* is a positive integer.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Hardware description languages such as VHDL, Verilog, and SystemVerilog natively support bit vectors as these are used to model storage elements like flip-flops, hardware busses and hardware signals in general.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] In hardware verification languages such as OpenVera, *e* and SystemVerilog, bit vectors are used to sample values from the hardware models, and to represent data that is transferred to hardware during simulations.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Common Lisp provides multi-dimensional bit arrays.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] A one-dimensional `bit-vector` implementation is provided as a special case of the built-in `array`, acting in a dual capacity as a class and a type specifier.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Bit arrays (and thus bit vectors) relies on the general `make-array` function to be configured with an element type of `bit`, which optionally permits a bit vector to be designated as dynamically resizable.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] The `bit-vector`, however, is not infinite in extent.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] A more restricted `simple-bit-vector` type exists, which explicitly excludes the dynamic characteristics.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Bit vectors are represented as, and can be constructed in a more concise fashion by, the *reader macro* `#**bits*`.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] In addition to the general functions applicable to all arrays, dedicated operations exist for bit arrays.
[src:succinct-index-structure/bit-array] Single bits may be accessed and modified using the `bit` and `sbit` functions and an extensive number of logical operations is supported.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] In computer science, an **FM-index** is a compressed full-text substring index based on the Burrows–Wheeler transform, with some similarities to the suffix array.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] It was created by Paolo Ferragina and Giovanni Manzini, who describe it as an opportunistic data structure as it allows compression of the input text while still permitting fast substring queries.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] The name stands for Full-text index in Minute space.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] It can be used to efficiently find the number of occurrences of a pattern within the compressed text, as well as locate the position of each occurrence.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] The query time, as well as the required storage space, has a sublinear complexity with respect to the size of the input data.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] The original authors have devised improvements to their original approach and dubbed it "FM-Index version 2".
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] A further improvement, the alphabet-friendly FM-index, combines the use of compression boosting and wavelet trees to significantly reduce the space usage for large alphabets.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] The FM-index has found use in, among other places, bioinformatics.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] Using an index is a common strategy to efficiently search a large body of text.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] When the text is larger than what reasonably fits within a computer's main memory, there is a need to compress not only the text but also the index.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] When the FM-index was introduced, there were several suggested solutions that were based on traditional compression methods and tried to solve the compressed matching problem.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] In contrast, the FM-index is a compressed self-index, which means that it compresses the data and indexes it at the same time.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] An FM-index is created by first taking the Burrows–Wheeler transform (BWT) of the input text.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] For example, the BWT of the string T = "abracadabra$" is "ard$rcaaaabb", and here it is represented by the matrix M where each row is a rotation of the text, and the rows have been sorted lexicographically.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] The transform corresponds to the concatenation of the characters from the last column (labeled L).
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] The BWT in itself allows for some compression with, for instance, move to front and Huffman encoding, but the transform has even more uses.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] The rows in the matrix are essentially the sorted suffixes of the text and the first column F of the matrix shares similarities with suffix arrays.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] How the suffix array relates to the BWT lies at the heart of the FM-index.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] It is possible to make a last-to-first column mapping LF(i) from an index i to an index j, such that F[j] = L[i], with the help of a table C[c] and a function Occ(c, k).
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] The last-to-first mapping can now be defined as LF(i) = C[L[i]] + Occ(L[i], i).
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] For instance, on row 9, L is a and the same a can be found on row 5 in the first column F, so LF(9) should be 5 and LF(9) = C[a] + Occ(a, 9) = 5.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] For any row i of the matrix, the character in the last column L[i] precedes the character in the first column F[i] also in T.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] Finally, if L[i] = T[k], then L[LF(i)] = T[k - 1], and using the equality it is possible to extract a string of T from L.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] The FM-index itself is a compression of the string L together with C and Occ in some form, as well as information that maps a selection of indices in L to positions in the original string T.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] The operation *count* takes a pattern P[1..p] and returns the number of occurrences of that pattern in the original text T.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] Since the rows of matrix M are sorted, and it contains every suffix of T, the occurrences of pattern P will be next to each other in a single continuous range.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] The operation iterates backwards over the pattern.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] For every character in the pattern, the range that has the character as a suffix is found.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] The new range is [C[r] + Occ(r, start-1) + 1 ..
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] 10 + 2] = [11..12], if start is the index of the beginning of the range and end is the end.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] This range over L is all the characters of T that have suffixes beginning with *ra*.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] The new range is [C[b] + Occ(b, start-1) + 1 ..
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] This range over L is all the characters that have a suffix that begins with *bra*.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] Now that the whole pattern has been processed, the count is the same as the size of the range: 8 - 7 + 1 = 2.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] If the range becomes empty or the range boundaries cross each other before the whole pattern has been looked up, the pattern does not occur in T.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] Because Occ(c, k) can be performed in constant time, count can complete in linear time in the length of the pattern: O(p) time.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] The operation *locate* takes as input an index of a character in L and returns its position i in T.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] To locate every occurrence of a pattern, first the range of character is found whose suffix is the pattern in the same way the *count* operation found the range.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] Then the position of every character in the range can be located.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] To map an index in L to one in T, a subset of the indices in L are associated with a position in T.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] If L[j] has a position associated with it, locate(j) is trivial.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] If it's not associated, the string is followed with LF(i) until an associated index is found.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] By associating a suitable number of indices, an upper bound can be found.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] *Locate* can be implemented to find *occ* occurrences of a pattern P[1..*p*] in a text T[1..*u*] in O(*p* + *occ* logε *u*) time with $O\left(H_{k}(T)+{{\log \log u} \over {\log ^{\epsilon }u}}\right)$ bits per input symbol for any *k* ≥ 0.
[src:succinct-index-structure/fm-index] The FM-Index is available in multiple languages, including C++, Java and Rust.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] In computer science, an **implicit data structure** or **space-efficient data structure** is a data structure that stores very little information other than the main or required data: a data structure that requires low overhead.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] They are called "implicit" because the position of the elements carries meaning and relationship between elements; this is contrasted with the use of pointers to give an *explicit* relationship between elements.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] Definitions of "low overhead" vary, but generally means constant overhead; in big O notation, *O*(1) overhead.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] A less restrictive definition is a succinct data structure, which allows greater overhead.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] An implicit data structure is one with constant *O*(1) space overhead (above the information-theoretic lower bound).
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] This latter definition is today more standard, and the still-looser notion of a data structure with non-constant but small *o*(*n*) overhead is today known as a succinct data structure, as defined by Jacobson (1988); it was referred to as **semi-implicit** by Munro & Suwanda (1980).
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] A fundamental distinction is between *static* data structures (read-only) and *dynamic* data structures (which can be modified).
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] Simple implicit data structures, such as representing a sorted list as an array, may be very efficient as a static data structure, but inefficient as a dynamic data structure, due to modification operations (such as insertion in the case of a sorted list) being inefficient.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] Similarly, a *null-terminated string* is an implicit data structure for a string (list of characters).
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] These are considered very simple because they are static data structures (read-only), and only admit the simple operation of iteration over the elements.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] Similarly simple is representing a multi-dimensional array as a single 1-dimensional array, together with its dimensions.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] For example, representing an *m* × *n* array as a single list of length *m·n*, together with the numbers *m* and *n* (instead of as a 1-dimensional array of pointers to each 1-dimensional subarray).
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] The elements need not be of the same type, and a table of data (a list of records) may similarly be represented implicitly as a flat (1-dimensional) list, together with the length of each field, so long as each field has uniform size (so a single size can be used per field, not per record).
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] A less trivial example is representing a sorted list by a *sorted array*, which allows search in logarithmic time by binary search.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] Contrast with a search tree, specifically a binary search tree, which also allows logarithmic-time search, but requires pointers.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] A sorted array is only efficient as a static data structure, as modifying the list is slow – unlike a binary search tree – but does not require the space overhead of a tree.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] An important example of an implicit data structure is representing a perfect binary tree as a list, in increasing order of depth, so root, first left child, first right child, first left child of first left child, etc.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] Such a tree occurs notably for an ancestry chart to a given depth, and the implicit representation is known as an *Ahnentafel* (ancestor table).
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] This can be generalized to a complete binary tree (where the last level may be incomplete), which yields the best-known example of an implicit data structure, namely the *binary heap*, which is an implicit data structure for a priority queue.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] This is more sophisticated than earlier examples because it allows multiple operations, and is an efficient *dynamic* data structure (it allows efficient modification of the data): not only **top**, but also **insert** and **pop**.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] More sophisticated implicit data structures include the beap (bi-parental heap).
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] The trivial examples of lists or tables of values date to prehistory, while historically non-trivial implicit data structures date at least to the Ahnentafel, which was introduced by Michaël Eytzinger in 1590 for use in genealogy.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] In formal computer science, the first implicit data structure is generally considered to be the sorted list, used for binary search, which was introduced by John Mauchly in 1946, in the Moore School Lectures, the first ever set of lectures regarding any computer-related topic.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] The binary heap was introduced in Williams (1964) to implement the heapsort.
[src:succinct-index-structure/implicit-data-structure] The notion of an implicit data structure was formalized in Munro & Suwanda (1980), as part of introducing and analyzing the beap.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] In computer science, a **range minimum query** (**RMQ**) solves the problem of finding the minimal value in a sub-array of an array of comparable objects.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] Range minimum queries have several use cases in computer science, such as the lowest common ancestor problem and the longest common prefix problem (LCP).
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] Given an array *A*[1 … *n*] of n objects taken from a totally ordered set, such as integers, the range minimum query RMQ*A*(*l*,*r*) =arg min *A*[*k*] (with 1 ≤ *l* ≤ *k* ≤ *r* ≤ *n*) returns the position of the minimal element in the specified sub-array *A*[*l* … *r*].
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] In a typical setting, the array A is static, i.e., elements are not inserted or deleted during a series of queries, and the queries to be answered on-line (i.e., the whole set of queries are not known in advance to the algorithm).
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] In this case a suitable preprocessing of the array into a data structure ensures faster query answering.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] A naive solution is to precompute all possible queries, i.e. the minimum of all sub-arrays of A, and store these in an array B such that *B*[*i*, *j*] = min(*A*[*i*…*j*]); then a range min query can be solved in constant time by array lookup in B.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] There are Θ(*n*²) possible queries for a length-n array, and the answers to these can be computed in Θ(*n*²) time by dynamic programming.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] As in the solution above, answering queries in constant time will be achieved by pre-computing results.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] However, the array will store pre-computed range minimum queries not for every range [*i*, *j*], but only for ranges whose size is a power of two.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] There are O(log *n*) such queries for each start position i, so the size of the dynamic programming table B is O(*n* log *n*).
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] After this pre-computing step, a query RMQ*A*(*l*,*r*) can now be answered in constant time by splitting it into two separate queries: one is the pre-computed query with range from l to the largest memoized value smaller than r.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] The other is the query of an interval of the same length that has r as its right boundary.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] These intervals may overlap, but since we are trying to compute the minimum rather than, for example, the sum of the numbers in the array, this does not matter.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] The overall result can thus be obtained, after the linearithmic time pre-computing, in constant time: the two queries can be answered in constant time and the only thing left to do is to choose the smaller of the two results.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] This solution does pre-computation in *O*(*n*) time.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] Its data structures use *O*(*n*) space and its data structures can be used to answer queries in logarithmic time.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] The array is first conceptually divided into blocks of size *s* = ⁠log *n*/4⁠.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] Then the minimum for each block can be computed in *O*(*n*) time overall and the minima are stored in a new array.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] For example, using the array *A* = [0,5,2,5,4,3,1,6,3] and a block size of 3 (for illustrative purposes only) yields the minimum array *A'* = [0,3,1].
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] Using the solution above, the sub-queries inside the blocks that are not fully contained in the query still need to be answered in constant time.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] There are at most two of those blocks: the block containing l and the block containing r.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] Constant time is achieved by storing the Cartesian trees for all the blocks in the array.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] For every such tree, the possible result for all queries need to be stored.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] This comes down to *s*2 or *O*(log2 *n*) entries.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] This means the overall size of the table is *O*(*n*).
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] To look up results efficiently, the Cartesian tree (row) corresponding to a specific block must be addressable in constant time.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] The solution is to store the results for all trees in an array and find a unique projection from binary trees to integers to address the entries.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] This can be achieved by doing a breadth-first-search through the tree and adding leaf nodes so that every existing node in the Cartesian tree has exactly two children.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] The integer is then generated by representing every inner node as a 0-bit and every leaf as a 1-bit in a bit-word (by traversing the tree in level-order again).
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] This leads to a size of ⁠log *n*/4⁠ for every tree.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] To enable random access in constant time to any tree, the trees not contained in the original array need to be included as well.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] An array with indices of ⁠log *n*/4⁠ bits length has size 2⁠log *n*/4⁠ = *O*(*n*).
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] RMQs are used as a tool for many tasks in exact and approximate string matching.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] Several applications can be found in Fischer and Heun (2007).
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] RMQs can be used to solve the lowest common ancestor problem and are used as a tool for many tasks in exact and approximate string matching.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] The LCA query LCA*S*(*v*, *w*) of a rooted tree *S* = (*V*, *E*) and two nodes *v*, *w* ∈ *V* returns the deepest node u (which may be v or w) on paths from the root to both w and v.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] Gabow, Bentley, and Tarjan (1984) showed that the LCA Problem can be reduced in linear time to the RMQ problem.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] It follows that, like the RMQ problem, the LCA problem can be solved in constant time and linear space.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] In the context of text indexing, RMQs can be used to find the LCP (longest common prefix), where LCP*T*(*i*, *j*) computes the LCP of the suffixes that start at indexes i and j in T.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] To do this we first compute the suffix array A, and the inverse suffix array *A*−1.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] We then compute the LCP array H giving the LCP of adjacent suffixes in A.
[src:succinct-index-structure/range-minimum-query] Once these data structures are computed, and RMQ preprocessing is complete, the length of the general LCP can be computed in constant time by the formula: LCP(*i*, *j*) = RMQH(*A*-1[*i*] + 1, *A*-1[*j*]), where we assume for simplicity that *A*-1[*i*] + 1 <= *A*-1[*j*] (otherwise swap).
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] In computer science, a **succinct data structure** is a data structure which uses an amount of space that is "close" to the information-theoretic lower bound, but (unlike other compressed representations) still allows for efficient query operations.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] The concept was originally introduced by Jacobson to encode bit vectors, (unlabeled) trees, and planar graphs.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] Unlike general lossless data compression algorithms, succinct data structures retain the ability to use them in-place, without decompressing them first.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] A related notion is that of a compressed data structure, insofar as the size of the stored or encoded data similarly depends upon the specific content of the data itself.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] Suppose that Z is the information-theoretical optimal number of bits needed to store some data.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] For example, a data structure that uses $2Z$ bits of storage is compact, $Z+{\sqrt {Z}}$ bits is succinct, $Z+\lg Z$ bits is also succinct, and $Z+3$ bits is implicit.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] Implicit structures are thus usually reduced to storing information using some permutation of the input data; the most well-known example of this is the heap.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] Succinct indexable dictionaries, also called *rank/select* dictionaries, form the basis of a number of succinct representation techniques, including binary trees, k -ary trees and multisets, as well as suffix trees and arrays.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] In other words, $\mathbf {rank} _{q}(x)$ returns the number of elements equal to q up to position x while $\mathbf {select} _{q}(x)$ returns the position of the x -th occurrence of q .
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] There is a simple representation which uses $n+o(n)$ bits of storage space (the original bit array and an $o(n)$ auxiliary structure) and supports **rank** and **select** in constant time.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] It uses an idea similar to that for range-minimum queries; there are a constant number of recursions before stopping at a subproblem of a limited size.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] The bit array B is partitioned into *large blocks* of size $l=\lg ^{2}n$ bits and *small blocks* of size $s=\lg n/2$ bits.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] For each large block, the rank of its first bit is stored in a separate table $R_{l}[0\dots n/l)$ ; each such entry takes $\lg n$ bits for a total of $(n/l)\lg n=n/\lg n$ bits of storage.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] Within a large block, another directory $R_{s}[0\dots l/s)$ stores the rank of each of the $l/s=2\lg n$ small blocks it contains.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] The difference here is that it only needs $\lg l=\lg \lg ^{2}n=2\lg \lg n$ bits for each entry, since only the differences from the rank of the first bit in the containing large block need to be stored.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] Thus, this table takes a total of $(n/s)\lg l=4n\lg \lg n/\lg n$ bits.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] A lookup table $R_{p}$ can then be used that stores the answer to every possible rank query on a bit string of length s for $i\in [0,s)$ ; this requires $2^{s}s\lg s=O({\sqrt {n}}\lg n\lg \lg n)$ bits of storage space.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] Thus, since each of these auxiliary tables take $o(n)$ space, this data structure supports rank queries in $O(1)$ time and $n+o(n)$ bits of space.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] In practice, the lookup table $R_{p}$ can be replaced by bitwise operations and smaller tables that can be used to find the number of bits set in the small blocks.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] This is often beneficial, since succinct data structures find their uses in large data sets, in which case cache misses become much more frequent and the chances of the lookup table being evicted from closer CPU caches becomes higher.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] Select queries can be easily supported by doing a binary search on the same auxiliary structure used for **rank**; however, this takes $O(\lg n)$ time in the worst case.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] A more complicated structure using $3n/\lg \lg n+O({\sqrt {n}}\lg n\lg \lg n)=o(n)$ bits of additional storage can be used to support **select** in constant time.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] In practice, many of these solutions have hidden constants in the $O(\cdot )$ notation which dominate before any asymptotic advantage becomes apparent; implementations using broadword operations and word-aligned blocks often perform better in practice.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] There is a succinct (static) dictionary which attains this bound, namely using ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+o({\mathcal {B}}(m,n))$ space.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] This structure can be extended to support **rank** and **select** queries and takes ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+O(m+n\lg \lg n/\lg n)$ space.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] Correct **rank** queries in this structure are however limited to elements contained in the set, analogous to how minimal perfect hashing functions work.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] This bound can be reduced to a space/time tradeoff by reducing the storage space of the dictionary to ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+O(nt^{t}/\lg ^{t}n+n^{3/4})$ with queries taking $O(t)$ time.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] If one wishes to support insertions and deletions, it is possible to achieve a space bound of ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+O(n/2^{(\log n)^{\Omega (1)}})$ while supporting each operation (insertion, deletion, rank, or select) in expected time $O(1+\log n/\log \log m)$ .
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] It is also possible to construct a indexible dictionary supporting rank (but not select) that uses fewer than $\textstyle {\mathcal {B}}(m,n)$ bits, so long as rank queries are limited to elements contained in the set.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] Such a dictionary is called a *monotone minimal perfect hash function*, and can be implemented using as few as $O(m\log \log \log n)$ bits.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] A succinct hash table, also known as a *succinct unordered dictionary,* is a data structure that stores m keys from a universe $\{0,1,\dots ,n-1\}$ using space $(1+o(1)){\mathcal {B}}(m,n)$ bits, and while supporting membership queries in constant expected time.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] The first dynamic succinct hash table was due to Raman and Rao in 2003.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] In the case where $n={\text{poly}}(m)$ , their solution uses space ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+O(m\log \log m)$ bits.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] Subsequently, it was shown that this space bound could be improved to ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+O(m\log \log \log \cdots \log m)$ bits for any constant number of logarithms and a little after that this bound was also optimal.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] The latter solution supports all operations in worst-case constant time with high probability.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] The first static succinct hash table was due to Pagh in 1999.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] In the case where $n={\text{poly}}(m)$ , their solution uses space ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+O(m(\log \log m)^{2}/\log m)$ bits, and supports *worst-case* constant-time queries.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] This bound was subsequently improved to ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+m/{\text{poly}}\log m$ bits, and then to ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+{\text{poly}}\log m$ bits.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] Whereas the first two solutions support worst-case constant-time queries, the final one supports constant expected-time queries.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] The final solution also requires access to a lookup table of size $n^{\epsilon }$ , but this lookup table is independent of the set of elements being stored.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] More recently, Hu et al. devised a solution that uses space ${\mathcal {B}}(m,n)+n^{\epsilon }$ while supporting worst-case constant-time queries.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] A string with an arbitrary length (Pascal string) takes *Z* + log(*Z*) space, and is thus succinct.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] When a sequence of variable-length items (such as strings) needs to be encoded, there are various possibilities.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] A direct approach is to store a length and an item in each record – these can then be placed one after another.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] This allows efficient next, but not finding the *k*th item.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] An alternative is to place the items in order with a delimiter (e.g., null-terminated string).
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] This uses a delimiter instead of a length, and is substantially slower, since the entire sequence must be scanned for delimiters.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] An alternative approach is out-of-band separation: the items can simply be placed one after another, with no delimiters.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] Item bounds can then be stored as a sequence of length, or better, offsets into this sequence.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] Alternatively, a separate binary string consisting of 1s in the positions where an item begins, and 0s everywhere else is encoded along with it.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] Given this string, the $select$ function can quickly determine where each item begins, given its index.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] This is *compact* but not *succinct,* as it takes 2*Z* space, which is O(*Z*).
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] The number of different binary trees on n nodes is ${\tbinom {2n}{n}}$ $/(n+1)$ .
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] For large n , this is about $4^{n}$ ; thus we need at least about $\log _{2}(4^{n})=2n$ bits to encode it.
[src:succinct-index-structure/succinct-data-structure] A succinct binary tree therefore would occupy only 2 bits per node.
[src:succinct-index-structure/wavelet-tree] The **wavelet tree** is a succinct data structure to store strings in compressed space.
[src:succinct-index-structure/wavelet-tree] It generalizes the $\mathbf {rank} _{q}$ and $\mathbf {select} _{q}$ operations defined on bitvectors to arbitrary alphabets.
[src:succinct-index-structure/wavelet-tree] Originally introduced to represent compressed suffix arrays, it has found application in several contexts.
[src:succinct-index-structure/wavelet-tree] The tree is defined by recursively partitioning the alphabet into pairs of subsets; the leaves correspond to individual symbols of the alphabet, and at each node a bitvector stores whether a symbol of the string belongs to one subset or the other.
[src:succinct-index-structure/wavelet-tree] The name derives from an analogy with the wavelet transform for signals, which recursively decomposes a signal into low-frequency and high-frequency components.
[src:succinct-index-structure/wavelet-tree] Let $\Sigma$ be a finite alphabet with $\sigma ={|\Sigma |}$ .
[src:succinct-index-structure/wavelet-tree] By using succinct dictionaries in the nodes, a string $s\in \Sigma ^{*}$ can be stored in ${|s|}H_{0}(s)+o({|s|}\log \sigma )$ , where $H_{0}(s)$ is the order-0 empirical entropy of s .
[src:succinct-index-structure/wavelet-tree] If the tree is balanced, the operations $\mathbf {access}$ , $\mathbf {rank} _{q}$ , and $\mathbf {select} _{q}$ can be supported in $O(\log \sigma )$ time.
[src:succinct-index-structure/wavelet-tree] A wavelet tree contains a bitmap representation of a string.
[src:succinct-index-structure/wavelet-tree] If we know the alphabet set, then the exact string can be inferred by tracking bits down the tree.
[src:succinct-index-structure/wavelet-tree] In this context, the rank of a position i in a bitvector b is the number of ones that appear in the first i positions of b .
[src:succinct-index-structure/wavelet-tree] Because the rank can be calculated in O(1) by using succinct dictionaries, any S[i] in string S can be accessed in $O(\log \sigma )$ time, as long as the tree is balanced.
[src:succinct-index-structure/wavelet-tree] Several extensions to the basic structure have been presented in the literature.
[src:succinct-index-structure/wavelet-tree] To reduce the height of the tree, multiary nodes can be used instead of binary.
[src:succinct-index-structure/wavelet-tree] The data structure can be made dynamic, supporting insertions and deletions at arbitrary points of the string; this feature enables the implementation of dynamic FM-indexes.
[src:succinct-index-structure/wavelet-tree] This can be further generalized, allowing the update operations to change the underlying alphabet: the Wavelet Trie exploits the trie structure on an alphabet of strings to enable dynamic tree modifications.
